caption: Delicious, fresh, and exceptinally well prepared and seasoned food. The Ohno Khauk soup is so good, with substantial and yummy noodles and coconut base. My husband and I shared one order plus a large plate of vegetable curry and that was plenty to satisfy our hunger. The staff we interacted with was exceptionally customer friendly.
Delicious food and flavors! The Ohno Khauk noodle soup is amazing.

I had heard a lot about this place, so I really wanted to like it - unfortunately it didn’t quite measure up. This was my first time trying Burmese food, so it could very well be that I went in with the wrong expectations... But I was left a bit underwhelmed. Nothing was inedible, but everything seemed like it could have used more flavor. On top of that, our order was missing the dessert item. When I called the restaurant to ask about the missing item, no one answered, even though it was only 5 minutes after closing. Kind of a bummer experience overall.

*COVID REVIEW*  I've been excited to try Thamee since it opened and was thrilled to find they had amazing vegetarian options during Restaurant Week. It did not disappoint!  The pickled tea leaves salad, coconut mushroom noodle soup, catfish soup, and sanwin makan (semolina cake that was basically cheesecake) were all typical Burmese and accessible at the same time.  They packaged and labeled each item perfectly which allowed us to pick it up with confidence and know exactly what was what when we got home.  I'll definitely be back 🇲🇲
We did take away and feasted on amazing flavors.  Went crazy for the curry Ohno Khauk Swe, Turmeric fried rice and citrus ginger thoke.  Love this place!  A winner on H Street and a DC gem!
Dopest flavors ever

There's so much love in Thamee's food. Everything is homemade, the portions are generous, and the staff in incredible. I loved their BIPOC market and the Native American wine was the best red I've had in years (Twisted Cedar). I can't wait to try the rest of their dishes.

Very gentrified. Not very authentic. Bland. Does not taste anywhere near burmese food should. Staff knew nothing of burmese culture or of the food and kept apologizing for the owner not being there. Sorry. I'm burmese and was highly disappointed.

Nice introduction to Burmese food. Not sure that I would go back as I found it to be flavorful but bland. Maybe I needed a bit of heat somewhere. The panko catfish was nice, definitely detected some nutmeg, bit still... catfish. The pork udon arrived not hot, just warm. The depth of flavor there was interesting but I still wanted more. I tasted the meatballs, big ok as I am not a big fan of gravy. Not mad at the food at all, just not sure I need to ever return. The service is amazing. Everyone is extremely nice and they will bend over backwards to make sure you are comfortable and understand the menu.

Thamee is amazing. Love having Burmese food on H St and love that it's women owned and run. The food, drinks, dessert are all delicious. The people are nice, welcoming, and believe in their community, people, and work. Love Thamee!!
Had a really good experience with Thamee's food and service and having hot food delivered to our home. Highly recommend the curry, tea salad and drinks to go.

Stumbled onto Thamee when I was out biking with my son today and what a treat!  The pork was tender and full of flavor, with a sour/vinegary pickle on the side that was just the right complement.  The watermelon salad fresh, crisp, and piquant with mint.  The limeade was fresh and not too sweet, just light and refreshing and very unique; I don't want to spoil the surprise but I'll just say it was unlike any other limeade.  Best of all the people who served us were so warm and friendly.  Experiencing Thamee made our day a memorable one.  Thank you for staying open and serving during coronavirus time!

There was a wait to pick up but there were social distancing markers so you knew where to be. I think it was more a communication issue with the customer in the front of the line not knowing they could go inside.  Once inside i gave my name. There's several items you can pick up like sauces and beers from local businesses. It took less then 5 minutes to get my head. I ordered ahead and arrived past my pickup time but my food was still super hot when i got home 20 minutes later.  The tandoori chicken sammie was a promotional item for Saturday sammies. Made by RAMMY Rising Culinary Star Nominee Chef Jocelyn Law. These flatbread sandwiches are made from parathas, flaky, unleavened breads originating from the Indian subcontinent.  My take? Honestly incredible. I was skeptical actually and after the first bite i was hooked! Seriously so good. 10/10 recommend if they bring it back. Also had the beef rendang and it was  Follow me on Instagram for more best bites: @alixtakesabite

Wonderful journey into Burmese cuisine. While I can't personally speak to "authenticity", the execution was incredible. Wonderful fish and curry-heavy menu. Vegetable dishes were particularly good and surprising. Slightly lacking in service detail and noise levels.

This was my first time eating Burmese food and I will definitely be going back (next time to try dinner)! We got the bottomless brunch that includes one app and one entree plus unlimited drinks (alcoholic or non) for $35. Everything we ordered was extremely tasty and filling. A special shout out to the vegetable samusas (app) and the Palata + Curry. The house made flatbread that came with the curry was phenomenal. The Breffis Sammy was also great; the milk bread was some of the best bread I’ve ever eaten and the tomatoes were so fresh. I also can’t forget to mention the staff. One of the owners welcomed us upon arrival and was so sweet the entire time.

The service here is exceptional. Everyone was attentive and knowledgeable. We had one of the best meals of our lives. Their signature curry is a must have. Glad we live nearby, because we are definitely going back.
We had 5 dishes and they were all delicious. We walked in on a busy Wednesday night but the staff still oozed hospitality and got us bar seats within 15 minutes. Can't wait to go back
Great food but missing some of the traditional elements of Burma. Still would recommend to anyone!
Amazing!

Our first Burmese food experience! Our server was very nice and helpful in explaining the dishes and various components that make each dish what they are. We thought the pricing for the Thamee Lay was off - you only get a small noodle dish, even though the pricing of the large noodles were much more in line with the mains. Our server's response was that it was the goal to not be so full? Made no sense to us. We ended up ordering several Lays and just ordered the Mohinga by itself. Our starters included spicy shoots & greens, lahpet thoke, and chicken/white flower mushroom, which we ordered with a side of garlic naan. The starters were pretty much all delicious. The lahpet thoke was my least favorite - it had an interesting flavoring of sourness with the bitterness of the tea leaves. Their garlic naan is so so yummy! The Mohinga was really delicious, hearty but not heavy curry broth with perfectly cooked noodles. We tried all 3 of the mains. The pazun hin's prawns were cooked so tender. The curried meatballs, while the curry sauce was really delicious, the meatballs were on the dry side. This curry sauce tastes delicious with the golden rice and dipping naan! Ma Jo's spicy tofu was just weird to us. It wasn't terrible but the taste was "why bother eating this, why bother making this". May have just been personal preference at our table. Our server was very kind and offered us another dish to replace it since we weren't fond of it, but we were already full and appreciatively declined the offer. We finished with the kulfi affogato which sounded so interesting on the menu, but was just ok - wouldn't order it if there were more creative dessert choices. Our server made our dinner a great experience, checked in with us consistently and really spoke to the food and elements.
Delicious food, incredibly nice atmosphere and amazing service. Can't wait to come back.

The service here was absolutely outstanding. We truly enjoyed our experience here. Everyone was fantastic, but we particularly want to thank Marcus for being such a great waiter; he made it a five star evening!  Also, the Ayu Ma cocktail was delicious - definitely give it a go if you enjoy a well-crafted cocktail.
One of my favorite places on H Street NE!
Great food and service. Everything was very delicious and the restaurant works to provide for all of their employees.  The tamarind punch was great

Your experience starts when you walk in the door and a wash of aromas and sounds roll over you like a warm breeze. Service is friendly and helpful, and the food is exciting and flavorful. Start with their fish fry, which is the perfect treatment of catfish. Crispy, peppery, it's the perfect flavor blast with the tomato chutney. There isn't a bad main on the menu. The Lay combo is a great value, and while I wouldn't go just for the desserts, they're a refreshing way to finish a rich meal.
Delicious food that is really interesting and different. Lovely service.
Food just so-so- mostly bland with some stand out dishes - meal was very expensive. The restaurant is very loud.  Some staff were great, some not so much.
Excellent food and service.
Food and service were ok and overpriced.  There are better choices in DC for a similar experience.

Food was good (especially the tea leaf salad and chicken mushroom salad). Noodle dishes were underwhelming. Service was good, but had reservation and were seated at the bar (stools didnt have a back rest).
My food was good. It was my first time but it wont be last
Exciting adventure of flavors. Loves it all.
It was incredible Burmese food,  BFC ( Burmese Fried Chicken) and Burmese fish soup. Best a customer service in DC. The best example of hospitality.

We came for the food but stayed for both the food and the drinks. Every cocktails is as pretty as it is tasty. By the time we finished eating we were too full for dessert. The fish shrimp, Khao suew and meatballs were all particularly tasty. The only miss was the veggie fritters. We'll definitely be back.
Great meal. The pickled tea leaf salad is a definite must have!
Don't miss the Beer Lao !!

Food tasted good but we felt ripped off. Crispy wonton cups was 14 dollars and they only give two small piece. Food is not authentic Burmese. They are more focused on making money than providing good authentic food. Won't go back here.
Amazing service, staff and food. Each dish was unique and full of flavor. Looking forward to going back!

In an unassuming setting (they have plastic tables that move at the slightest touch), the price was very assuming. The food is mediocre. The portion is way too small for their price. The service was the only redeeming quality that made me give three stars. This is a place where you go try an exotic food, but only for trying. Will probably never go back again.

What an incredible variety of flavors and textures. The staff Was patient and extremely knowledgeable. I was never lucky enough to visit Burma, but I now I sampled some flavors of the country. Vegetarian, gluten and dairy free options. It is a must try..
Amazing!!! Food was so good. Ambience is great. Don't sleep on this spot!
Very impressive - both the food and the service. Every single thing we had - tea leaf salad, chicken curry, branzino, cocktails, dessert - was delicious!
I cant wait to go back again, need to try the rest of their menu

Great food and service! I’ve had Burmese food a few times before and Thamee did not disappoint! I’m vegetarian/mostly vegan and the options were great. We got the curry noodles with mushrooms and the spicy tofu (which my friend was hesitant to try because he thought it would be boring but it ended up being his favorite!) along with the tea salad and homemade garlic naan. Cute location but it seems they also cater to groups, which is good to know. Definitely recommend!

The food is excellent. Add to the list of must eat places in DC.  Wonderful flavors and very fresh ingredients, you won't be disappointed.  This was the first time having Burmese food and I will Definitely eat here again.

Great brunch! I would highly recommend the brunch experience. All of the food and drinks were delicious, and it was nice to be able to get bottomless alcohol and no alcohol drinks (the milk tea was great on a cold morning).  The service definitely matched the food as well.
The food was extraordinary but desert was galeez

Tried Burmese food here for the first time today.  Wow!  It was the culinary equivalent of walking out into a beautiful, lush valley, surrounded by snow-capped mountain peaks, and three moons.  Then you ask yourself, where am I, this is so beautiful?  I had the same experience in my mouth today over a fantastic brunch.  There was a lushness of completely unfamiliar, delicious flavors flowing forth like a riptide.  SO GOOD.  The service was friendly and efficient and helpful.  Will definitely visit again.

Attentive and friendly staff with a menu that is vegetarian friendly. On the pricier side - expect to play at least $30 per person - but worth it if you are interested in tasting great Burmese food. The tea salad in particular is worth ordering, as it is the only place in the US where that specific salad is offered (according to our waiter!)

The overall impression is that is that The food is average the prices are high. We paid close to $200 for 3 people and we left hungry. On the plus side, thhrinks were nice sevice was very attentive. They should invest in stable tablesband chairs, so there is less of a fast food feel to the place to justify their prices.
Cool dining interesting cuisine salads were not so special try the meatballs and the nan bread. Fish was poorly cooked almost raw. Cocktails were good.
A cool dinning experience. The staff is really friendly and the food unique. I've never had anything like the tea salad. We heard they have a brunch but yet to try it.

Now that Thamee has been open for a few months, I was invited back to experience it again and wow. I am so glad I gave it another chance. The co-owners' mission is to normalize Burmese food in the USA. With food as tasty as at Thamee, mission accomplished. Thamee is worth a try, even if it feels outside of your comfort zone. Here's why:  1) Space: It feels like home. The staff from the chef to the co-owner to the bartenders all treat each other and you like family. It's the warmest entrance you'll have at a DC restaurant and it doesn't end throughout your visit.  2) Food: It is really good. There are a few items that may make your head turn like the wontons with chicken gizzards, but every single item (including the gizzards) are excellent. The stand outs- the green tea salad is full of flavor and better than any salad I've had at a Burmese restaurant (If you like Burma Superstar in San Francisco, Thamee's salad is better), the tofu (wow- best tofu we've had. It's made from chickpeas and soy-free), curry beef meatballs, and the kulfi affogato. Most items we will craze sending us back to Thamee time and time again.  3) Drinks: Okay, the cocktails surprised us. They recently released their fall cocktail menu and it's on point. We had six of the eight drinks. Each one complimented the food well. Each drink is among the best and most creative we've had in D.C., but the winner was the Ayu Ma with coconut oil-washed mezcal, banana liqueur, rhubarb amaro, cilantro-lemongrass syrup, orange bitters, and egg white. I don't love mezcal and my wife doesn't like banana, but we both LOVED this drink. All their drinks bridge the gap between more stiff and sweet drinks. No matter your preference, you'll LOVE their drinks.  We're soooo glad we went back. Thamee just became our regular spot.  If you want unique, fine dining in an accessible environment, come to Thamee and stay awhile! ____________________________________________________________________ Thamee is the new Burmese restaurant that replaced my favorite restaurant in DC, Sally's Middle Name. If you were a fan of its predecessor, you'll recognize the space. The new owners did very little to change the space, which I appreciate.  Thamee is from the creators behind Toli Moli in Union Market (I love Toli Moli and their buns!). The owners have a personal connection to Burma and tell an incredible story. They want to introduce quality Burmese food to Washington, D.C. To do that, they invest time and energy in gathering the very best ingredients for their dishes.  That said, I left unimpressed with the food. With media attention, I thought Thamee would be one of the best meals I'll have in the city. That wasn't the case. Now I am wondering if I don't like Burmese food or if they could do a better job on the food. I want to think its the latter.  I ordered the white mushroom and chicken dish, which was good, but not life-changing. The prawn and tomato dish was decent. The meeshay was GREAT and my favorite dish.  What was odd was that we ordered the eggplant and cauliflower curry. It came out with no cauliflower, very little eggplant and TONS of tomatoes. We asked the server about it and he said they messed up. He brought a new dish with some cauliflower, but still with an overload of tomatoes. I love a good tomato, but the description on the menu doesn't mention tomatoes. For dominating the dish, I was surprised by that.  The drinks were just okay and the service, sadly, not good. We sat at the bar on a Monday (they close Tuesday since most restaurants close Monday- smart move) and it took about 20 minutes for the server to notice us. Once he did, he disappeared for another 20 minutes. Our entire experience lasted 2.5 hours because our server was so inattentive. What made up for it was the owner. She is a true delight and someone you'd want to hang out with!  I definitely want to go back, because I want to love Thamee, but my first experience was a 3-star one.
Incredible flavors, engaged servers, and large portions.

The 3 course dinner with cocktails was an awesome choice! I’d tell you what we ordered but our waiter told us it was changing the next day. I’m looking forward to going back and trying their fall menu.

We essentially ordered all the dishes. The food was generally good, and the prices were reasonable for the quantities ordered. I was torn between a 3 and 4 star, but I am downgrading because the recollection of the bad dishes has outweighed the positives of the good dishes. We ordered the pork belly, and it was served somewhere south of room temperature. I like pork fat in all of its forms, but rubbery is not one of its optimal forms.
Found out about this place during the H street festival. Small place but it packs alot of flavor. The food is amazing and the punch packs a punch and taste great. I'll be back for the dinner menu.
Love the boozy coconut
This place has excellent Burmese food. Be prepared to be surprised by the flavours. I would particularly recommend the Khow Suey, which is very well done. The mango sorbet was also excellent.

Went for brunch, very friendly service by Jojo, Jordan and the rest of the team. Ordered the breffix sammy, the combo of the sweet milk bread with eggs, scallions and aioli was so so good. Would definitely come back and try the other dishes which also sound and look delicious.

Best restaurant I’ve been to in a while! The food was fantastic and the service was incredible. We were having a going-away dinner and it could’ve been a bummer but our experience here made sure we stayed in a great mood. Can’t wait to come back and we highly recommend it. It’s the new gem of DC!
I highly recommend this place- the food and the service were incredible!

I really wanted to love Thamee. Great story, lots of good press, but was wishing the food and service was just a bit better. Two experience menus for two people was a TON of food, I had enough for dinner the next night. I'd recommend a la carte.  My date and I did the experience menu including the cocktails for $55 each. We did the Shrimp + Buthee fritters, Gin Those, Pork + Picked Mango Curry with Golden Rice, the Dan Bauk Chicken, White flower mushroom + chicken, and the Mohinga plus the sorbet.  The fritters were good but the Dan Bauk Chicken could have been great but it was severely undercooked. I showed the server and she winced at how underdone it was. She offered to cook up another order so I could take it to-go, but one underdone chicken was enough for me (no offer or drinks or a discount)...my date's favorite was the pork + pickled mango curry. I didn't really have a favorite.  The tables are also really unstable so watch out!  Overall the place has a great vibe, the food could be improved, but I'm all for supporting a woman owned minority business, so check it out! I'd for sure go back for drinks and an appetizer.
Great food and service! Get the Thamee experience!

Very approachable introduction to Burmese food. I really like the decor and the ambiance of the restaurant. Food was delicious and good size portions to share allowing lots of variety. Owner is amazingly nice and extremely welcoming. She has such a passion for her food it's worth checking out.
Amazing food, atmosphere, and friendliness! Always a great time!

From top to bottom, the whole experience was incredible. I did the Thamee experience meal at the bar, and had a few cocktails. The ambience, service, and food were all incredible. Toyz and Simone both greeted me and provided excellent service! Definitely try the Mohinga!
Very good food and cocktails. Sat at the bar and had great service. My favorite dish was the prawns which our server recommended. Enjoyable meal all around!

This is a 4.5.  They have some pretty impressive flavors among the dishes served. The tea leaf salad was the least enjoyable, but could be a new flavor profile that was beyond me. It's acidic and super bitter. I could almost get on board, but it was just too much.  The deep fried shrimp and vegetables was very good. It was no ordinary batter. The pork with the tomato sause with pickled mango was unreal. It sounds unusual, but the flavor was amazing. The Naan was very good, but a tad pricey. The rice - well seasoned and accompanied the coconut curry very well. I would definitely come back.

We had such a lovely experience all around: the service was incredibly attentive and fast, even on a Friday night. The host suggested we sit t the bar. The food was both rich in flavor and subtle at the same time

The food, the service and the experience at Thamee is amazing. Every dish from starter to salad to main dish to dessert is a flavourful experience of Burmese cuisine. The drinks ranging from local and Asian beer to custom cocktails pair deliciously with all of the dishes available. Most of all, the srvice was top notch. Our waiter was enjoyable, knowledgable and quite passionate about the experience one has at Thamee. Wow. We look forward to returning again and having a delicious experience at Thamee.

Don't miss! Reasonable prices and so delicious! They didn't have prices available on board outside so we actually almost passed this place up. Glad we didn't! The mohinga (Myanmar national dish) is PHENOMENAL (not an exaggeration). I cannot understand what all spices make it so amazing, but it was heaven. The rest of our food was also really good, great date night spot, waitstaff was attentive and helpful. A great spot. We didn't try drinks but I saw others, they looked good. They have a neat little vegetables w/sauce they bring you in the beginning (no charge) also was good.

Probably the most vibrant and ingratiating place I’ve dined at since coming to DC. I’m a bit more laid back than your average bear when it comes to customer service expectations — I’ll happily take a surly soup slinger in a Soviet Stolovaya as long as said soup is warm. But the people here are genuinely warm, and clearly working hard to build a reputation on H Street for excellent cuisine and service. Count me among the converted. Four members of staff attended to me throughout my stay; they’re really working hard to serve and educate customers on their offerings.  I had the brunch with Burmese tea leave salad (fermented leaves are flown in from Myanmar, as staff explained), and the cat fish hash, which managed to shock a guy whose eaten ant egg soup and century eggs in his day. A really unique, sit back and take it in, sapor. Everything was the perfect balance of delicious and healthy, letting the delicate medley of ingredients express themselves without overwhelming via cheap culinary tricks. The bottomless beverages were balanced and delicious. Music the perfect volume, the restaurant bright and open. I’ll definitely be back.

What an experience. Love the food, love the owners, love the opportunity to enjoy Burmese cuisine in a bright, fun, positive restaurant space. Ordered some fresh naan to mop up the extra coconut curry sauce and was overcome with a case of the giggles at how good it was.
The service was incredible, everyone was so kind and thoughtful. Food was amazing - you must get the shrimp fritters!

I ordered chai, vegetable samosas and cat fish which is wrapped in banana leaf, everything was awesome. Staff is very professional and friendly Zeus at bar was great. Spl the restaurant  interior is so interesting the Fisher net hanging on  ceiling wall art, color full napkins and always smiling staff.

The food is blander than it is authentically, I think because they offer the chili in oil on the side as option. It should not be optional! Great atmosphere and seems to be a lovely team running this place. Some work to do on the balance between true Burmese (oily and spicy and served over white rice) what Americans will like (healthy and not spicy) but I have high hopes. [I am not Burmese, but lived there for a while]
Such amazing food and excellent service. Can't wait to go back
decor is cozy but clean. A great mix of color and hipness. Food was absolutely stunning for brunch. The catfish curry is a must, and the cocktails are to die for. Unique and delicious.
Tom Sietsema is so wrong on this place. Everything was either incredibly over-or-under seasoned. Terrible. Don’t go.

The pickled tea leaf salad was delicious. The waitress shared that they ship the tea leaves from Burma and this is the only restaurant in the US you can get them at. I wish I had gotten x5 of them rather then splitting one amongst the three of us.  The fiancee got the chicken coconut curry and she loved it. I tried the sauce (as I am vegetarian) and for me it was a little too sweet but I guess I am a bit more critical of food. It's also important to note I only tried the sauce, not the dish as a whole with the noodles, chicken, and onions.  BFF got prawns and tomatoes. Didn't want to try but she loved it and had a very satisfied food face.  I got the cauliflower and eggplant. One of two main vegetarian dishes. TBH it sucked. The eggplants were not cooked equally, some crunchy and some rubbery. The dish itself lacked seasoning and mostly tasted like tomatoes. I love tomatoes but it doesn't serve as enough flavor for the dish. In addition, it took around 7 minutes between when my fiancee and BFF got their dish and when I got my dish. They were half way done by the time mine arrived. This is why I felt forced to lower the stars.  We ended the meal with one plate of the dessert of the day. I enjoyed it but i wish the bread was bigger. But my god, that buttery naan was yummy. Ice cream was quite interesting.

Delicious meal and a pleasant experience here. The staff was kind and attentive, and it seemed like they put a lot of care in each of their dishes. I really loved the restaurant decor - true to the restaurant's Burmese identity and simple but not overdone. We ordered the tea leaf salad, coconut curry with mushroom, cauliflower & pickled mango, and the palata & scoops. I highly recommend all of them! Would love to come back for brunch. As a note - you may have to verify if certain dishes are vegan even if they're labeled that way on the menu (ex. the coconut curry comes with egg). I only wish that there was a vegetarian version of the tea leaf salad :)

A neighborhood gem.  We really needed a place like this on H St where you can get great food in a warm but hip atmosphere at a good price.  From the vegetables with authentic fish sauce dressing you get when you sit, to the amazing hand pulled ramen noodles, the food is legit and the flavors are delicious.  The hosts really care about their guests and the service was solid.  I would highly recommend!
Food was good & service was excellent
Incredible food and awesome people. Had like 5-6 dishes between my friend and I. It was all great but the mango pork was the best. And a hibiscus IPA? So good. They really make you feel welcome here.
Carefully handcrafted culinary delights, fresh cocktails and mocktails of Burmese cuisine. Delightful!
This was my first experience de with Burmese food, and it was awesome. You’ll definitely get some unique dishes here. Strongly recommend, especially the tea leaf salad and the signature cocktails.

Real Burmese tea leaves - yum! Such a unique menu. Food was perfect/exquisite, service was exceptional, atmosphere is light and warm.  Simone, Nate, and Jordan really took care of us. We felt so welcomed, and a part of their family.  #porkandmangofire #faloodamust

Delicious expertly prepared food, friendly attentive service, bright and modern space.  This spot is a great addition to the neighborhood.  My first time trying Burmese food.  I was impressed.  The food is very tasty without being overly seasoned.  The flavors are subtle and you can tell they use quality ingredients.  Menu prices were a fair value for the quality, and in line with my expectations for the neighborhood.  It would be nice to see some daily specials, happy hour deals, or loyalty program to get people in the door on a recurring basis. The staff seemed to all be really invested in ensuring we had a positive experience.  They also have a decent sized bar with some fun looking cocktails.  The drink I had was $10 which was the lower end of the range.  I don't often pay that much for a drink, but would say it was worth it.

My friend and I were very excited to try Burmese food but unfortunately we left hungry, underwhelmed and unhappy. We paid $60 each for the tasting menu and all we got were 2 appetizers, 1 main dish and 1 dessert to share. For $120 we could have gotten at least 6 dishes from their regular menu and would probably be much happier. I have done tasting menus countless times and they usually have 5-6 dishes so we were very surprised when they offered to bring dessert next. When we brought up the fact that we at least expected a dessert each, they did give us a second one but the manager (or owner) didn’t seem pleased. The staff were amazing and would give 5 stars for them but I cannot in good conscience give more than 2 stars to this place based on portions and taste.
Incredible cocktails and excellent food - I wasn't sure what to expect but I was blown away. Try the fried shrimp and buthee!
Excellent food, excellent cocktails!! Very chic, but laid back vibe. So glad this gem is in my neighborhood.
Great place on H street  - the food was flavorful, the service was great and the ambience was upbeat. Never knew I liked Burmese food!

Awesome and unique new spot on H street. Flavorful, delicious Burmese food. We had the chicken curry noodle and the pork and mango dish. Also had a side of the golden rice. Everything was sooooo good. Flavor was amazing. Great spice levels and all. The setting and vibe of the space is perfect as well. Loved our meal here and can’t wait to come back!
